    <h1>My Canon Event</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">School has ended and a new path is about to begin. Looking back at a Grade 5 English class, a teacher's sudden question, and the specific moment that changed how I saw my own potential forever.</p>
    <div class="article-meta">
      <span>Nakshatra RP</span>
      <span>·</span>
      <span>May 31, 2024</span>
      <span>·</span>
      <span>2 min read</span>
    </div>
  </header>
  
  <article class="article-body">
  
    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>“It’s the teacher that makes the difference, not the classroom.” – Michael Morpurgo</p>
    </div>
  
    <p>School has ended and your friendly neighbourhood blogger is counting down to the start of university life, which is just a few weeks away. It has been a while since I enjoyed a vacation free from academic stress and holiday homework. The last time was back in Grade 1 when my biggest concerns were sleeping, playing, and instructing my friend on how to make cookies over the phone, despite never having baked them myself. Fast forward 12 years, and here I am, back to my default settings - still never tried to bake cookies!</p>
  
    <p>Looking back, I realize how my life could have taken many alternate paths if it weren't for the people I've met along the way. Maybe there's a universe where Nakshatra bakes delicious cookies or one where she's a crafting whiz; lost versions of who I could have been. Regardless, I'm grateful for the experiences that have shaped me into who I am today. One particular person I would never forget is my Grade 5 English teacher. I still recall the first day of the academic year when she eyed me for talking among ourselves while somebody else was introducing herself. Of course, she's not the first or the last teacher who caught me talking and being inattentive in class, but she will always remain in my memory as the teacher who saw something in me - something worth nurturing.</p>
  
    <p>Those early years are crucial in one's lifetime and the way a child is treated can lay a foundation for who he/she grows into adult life. She was the kind of teacher who made every child feel seen and heard. She was the first who asked me why I lost a few marks in an exam; a question which shocked me at the time, since most people just used to be glad I passed. I don't remember my grades from back then, but that was the first time I had someone to hold me accountable for my performance and appreciate me whenever I did well. She pushed me to excel not just in academics but also in my talents. She noticed a shy voice that could sing and convinced me to perform on the school radio. When I published my first newspaper article in Grade 6, she eagerly sought out the paper in our school library to read it. We were taught by her for two consecutive years and those years changed my self-perception and gave me an identity that I carried into high school. Her belief in me opened a window into my potential, motivating me whenever I felt like I wasn't working up to my potential. She was empathetic and kind, yet set high standards for me to achieve.</p>
  
    <p>My canon event was having Ms. Suraja as my class teacher, who brought about a twist in my school life and paved the way for who I am today. I'm forever thankful for the support and sensitivity she showed me during those years, and I want her to know that we are still immensely inspired by her.</p>
  
